{"title": "missing", "links": "#about-the-journal", "content": ".", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "#publish-with-us", "content": "CAR-T cell therapies involve removing immune cells called T cells from a person with cancer, and genetically altering them so that they produce proteins \u2014 called chimeric antigen receptors, or CARs \u2014 that recognize cancer cells. The cells are then reinfused into the person, in the hope that they will seek out and destroy tumours.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/nature/subscribe", "content": "In the years since Olson\u2019s treatment, five CAR-T cell therapies have been approved by the US Food and Drug Administration, to treat leukaemias, lymphomas and myelomas. June estimates that tens of thousands of people have received CAR-T cell treatment.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/my-account/alerts/subscribe-journal?list-id=1", "content": "\n ", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "http://feeds.nature.com/nature/rss/current", "content": "Building better CAR-T therapies", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "/", "content": "But the therapy is expensive, risky and technically demanding. It remains a last resort, to be used when all other treatments have failed. Despite the treatment\u2019s success for Olson, not everyone experiences durable remission of their cancer. In the beginning, only about 25-35% of CAR-T cell recipients with chronic lymphocytic leukaemia experienced a complete remission of their cancer, says Porter. With refinement, that percentage has increased over the years, he says, but some of these initial successes still lead to relapse. Tracking the treatment long-term could reveal clues as to what factors are important for lasting CAR-T cell success.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "/nature/articles?type=news", "content": "For more than ten years, Porter and his colleagues analysed the CAR-T cells in Olson and one other person treated in 2010, tracing the cells\u2019 evolution and looking for any signs of safety concerns.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "#author-0", "content": "They found that the CAR T cells persisted, but the characteristics of the population shifted over time. Soon after infusion, a prominent population of T cells called CD8", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "/search?author=\"Heidi Ledford\"", "content": " cells emerged. These are sometimes called killer T cells, and can identify and destroy cells that display unusual proteins, such as ", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/query.fcgi?cmd=search&term=%22Heidi%2BLedford%22", "content": " or ", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?as_q=&btnG=Search+Scholar&as_sauthors=%22Heidi%2BLedford%22", "content": ".", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=Last-resort+cancer+therapy+holds+back+disease+for+more+than+a+decade&url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fd41586-022-00241-0", "content": "But over the years, a different type of CAR T cell became dominant. CD4", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fd41586-022-00241-0", "content": " T cells can take on a variety of functions in the immune system, but the researchers showed that both study participants had CD4", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "mailto:?subject=Last-resort cancer therapy holds back disease for more than a decade&body=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Farticles%2Fd41586-022-00241-0", "content": " cells with characteristics suggesting that they would be capable of killing leukaemia cells.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "/articles/d41586-022-00241-0.pdf", "content": "Olson and the other participant now have no signs of leukaemia. It\u2019s unclear whether the CAR T cells killed all the leukaemia cells soon after they were introduced, or if the cells that continue to patrol are able to destroy any leukaemia cells before they reach detectable levels.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "#ref-CR1", "content": "\n ", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-020-02675-w", "content": "Highly mutated cancers respond better to immune therapy", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/articles/508024a", "content": "\u201cThe potential impact of CAR T is tremendous,\u201d says Nirali Shah, a paediatric haematologist at the US National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland. This study \u201cgives you a proof of concept about the safety of having long-term persistence and integration of the T cells into your body\u201d.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-022-00063-0", "content": "It remains to be seen, she adds, how well the findings from these two individuals with chronic lymphocytic leukaemia will translate to other diseases. Efforts are underway to use CAR-T cell approaches to treat solid tumours, such as prostate tumours and the devastating brain cancer glioblastoma. In January, researchers reported success in using the cells to destroy scar tissue in the heart \u2014 an approach that could one day be used to treat cardiac fibrosis", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://www.nature.com/articles/d41586-019-00143-8", "content": ".", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "#ref-CR2", "content": "In the years after his treatment, Olson returned to his career in medical diagnostics. He committed to staying healthy, and his son talked him into running half marathons. \u201cIf my cancer was gone, I certainly didn\u2019t want to die of a heart attack,\u201d he says. Eventually, he decided to go public with the story of his recovery, and serve as a mentor for other people with cancer.", "images": []},
{"title": "missing", "links": "https://doi.org/10.1038%2Fs41586-021-04390-6", "content": "He tries to give them hope, he says: \u201cIf there isn\u2019t a cure for their cancer today, there\u2019s a reasonable chance that around the corner, there\u2019s going to be one.\u201d", "images": []},
